ling memoirs of Andrea Ashworth, Augusten Burroughs, Robert Drewe, Mary Karr, Frank McCourt, Dave Pelzer, and Lorna Sage, among many others. Drawing on trauma and memory studies and theories of authorship and readership, Contesting Childhood offers commentary on the triumphs, trials, and tribulations that have shaped this genre. Douglas examines the content of the narratives and the limits of their representations, as well as some of the ways in which autobiographies of youth have become politically important and influential. This study enables readers to discover how stories configure childhood within cultural memory and the public sphere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAutobiographical memory. 0aCollective memory. 0aMemoryxSocial aspects. 0aPsychic trauma. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354915640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813549156423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813549156.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK